The Familiar at the New Anti-Semitism
Why do so many survivors of the Holocaust feel emerging threats to Judaism, even before they become generally visible?
Because they know that ostensibly "harmless" hints can escalate into accusations and ultimately lead to legally entrenched discrimination.
At that point, hysteria then sets in.
The survivors sound the alarm because they know what is at stake.
By doing so, they strengthen our democracies in a way that only they can.
We listen to the survivors so that we too may survive.
Since the first round of the French presidential elections has made it clear that we have every reason to listen.
But not only demagogues like Jean-Marie Le Pen or other unrefined right-wing extremists in Europe cause difficulties.
In the 20th century, individuals who saw themselves as "intellectuals" often became the foot soldiers of fascism or communism, without joining a party with the corresponding ideological background.
In the 21st century, we are dealing with people - the "educated middle class" in conjunction with the mass media, politics, government, and universities - who condemn Israel in a language that often recalls that of the foot soldiers of these anti-democratic movements.
It is not yet the majority opinion in the Western world - not yet, thank goodness - but it is the voices of a powerful and influential minority.
At this point, mention should be made of the example of the French ambassador to the United Kingdom: Recently, he referred to Israel as "this damned little country" during a dinner party in London.
His crude language is not particularly alarming.
What is alarming, however, are the reactions to it.
Neither was he recalled by his government nor did the Blair government call for his recall. In the public eye, the affair was dismissed as just another scandal.
The French press presented the ambassador seriously as a victim of British tabloid journalism rather than his own deplorable attitude.
Unfortunately, the French ambassador to the United Kingdom has several allies among Europe's elite.
Ambassador Bernard, however, has served us: Through him, it has become clear just how widespread these new anti-Semitic sentiments are.
As a columnist so aptly put it: Israel has become a hate object, whose naming one dares not utter.
We, however, are not only entitled to, but even obligated to utter it.
In the face of daily attacks on Jews and synagogues in France, we cannot remain silent.
It is a shame for all of Europe that so many French Jews cannot send their children to school without having to worry about their safety.
Anti-Semitic incidents are also being reported elsewhere. In Berlin and London, in Switzerland, Italy, Sweden, the Netherlands, and parts of Eastern Europe.
We cannot remain silent about the increasingly everyday denial of the Holocaust. Nor can we remain silent about the comparisons that anti-Semites and anti-Zionists draw between Israel and the Third Reich.
While Israeli soldiers are portrayed as rapists and cold-blooded murderers in a Palestinian television broadcast, a Syrian newspaper wrote that we must "confront the new Nazi plague that is emerging in Israel."
The Mufti of Jerusalem said: "It's not my fault that Hitler hated Jews. They are almost hated everywhere".
While broadcasting a Friday prayer service on Palestinian television, the imam called on Muslims to show "no mercy to the Jews. Wherever you are, kill them and these Americans, who are just like them."
What we should think about in the context of anti-Semitism is that it always starts with the Jews but never ends with them.
If left unchecked, Jew-hatred almost always leads to attacks on other groups and minorities and ultimately undermines democratic institutions and the rule of law.
The fight against anti-Semitism is therefore the task of both Jews and non-Jews.
The targets in this fight are less clear than ever before, because a remarkable aspect of modern anti-Semitism is its flexibility.
Although the target of anti-Semitism remains the same - to attack Jews - it nonetheless changes its face, strategy, justifications, and even vocabulary.
Originally, the Jewish religion was the target.
As this hatred did not subside, the Jews were either deported or killed.
When the theory of racism cast its spell on people in the 19th century, Jews were attacked because of their association with a supposedly evil race.
With the existence of the State of Israel as a source of pride and protection for most Jews, Zionism is today discredited as a racist ideology.
I do not equate criticism of Israel with anti-Semitism.
It is certainly legitimate to stand critically against certain political strategies and decisions of Israel, just as it is with other nations.
Anti-Zionism is however becoming increasingly similar to anti-Semitism.
Anti-Zionists sometimes claim they are not against the Jews, but "only" against the Jewish state.
One would imagine someone saying: "I'm only against the existence of the United Kingdom, but I'm not anti-British!"
Or when someone claimed: "I love the Swedish people, but Sweden should be abolished."
One wouldn't believe them.
It's challenging to love or respect a people, but to despise their state.
And yet, there are people in the context of Israel who claim to be able to do exactly that.
In various UN organizations, insults against Israel are on the agenda.
The demonization of the only democratic state entity in the Middle East is a core point of this new anti-Semitism.
When Israel is described as the "enemy of all that is good and the source of all evil", the "doctrine of contempt" is being circulated within the UN, as expressed by Professor Irwin Cotler, a Canadian parliamentarian.
This constant portrayal of a nation as an enemy of humanity is in truth a campaign against the Jewish people.
So lie at the root of the numerous anti-Semitic incidents in many countries the demonizations of Israel, which resort to anti-Semitic terminology.
Attacks on synagogues are often triggered by the use of this defamatory language in the context of the Middle East.
In comparison to previous anti-Semitic outbursts, today's anti-Semitism is less about attacking individual Jews and more about a collective attack on the "Jewish collective," that is, the State of Israel.
Such attacks have, however, triggered a chain reaction of assaults on individual Jews and Jewish institutions throughout Europe and Latin America.
Earlier, the most dangerous anti-Semites were those who wanted to make the world free of Jews.
The most dangerous anti-Semites today are those who want to make the world free of the Jewish state.
